# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1998-greater-london-authority-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The **first election to the County Council of London** took place on 17 January 1889.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The council was elected by First Past the Post with each elector having two votes in the two-member seats.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Although the election was not contested on a party political basis, soon after the election, the majority of councillors formed the Progressive Party.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The council replaced the Metropolitan Board of Works, which was not a directly elected body.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The London Municipal Reform League, a mixture of liberals and socialists, had long called for the establishment of an elected council for the city.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Many of the candidates in the 1889 election were supporters of the league, while a second grouping were opponents of the league.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] This was a similar arrangement to that on the London School Board.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Some candidates stood as independent of either grouping, many of whom were supported by local Conservative Party associations.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] In total, 32 candidates admitted to being sponsored by the Conservative Party or Liberal Party.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Some candidates proposed sweeping reforms, which fell outside the powers of the new council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Others, including Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery, argued that voters should elect the most competent candidates.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] *The Times* agreed with this assessment, but complained that many candidates were insufficiently well-known that voters could assess their competence.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The paper also argued that "in no case can it be right to give support to a socialist".
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] The majority of successful candidates were supporters of the London Municipal Reform League, and after the election, they formed the Progressive Party.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Their opponents did not form a political party, but did collaborate on the council as the Moderates, to the extent of having a whip.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] However, the groupings were initially not rigid, and many votes were conducted according to individual's consciences.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] 29 candidates had been members of the Metropolitan Board of Works, but only six of them won election.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] It was not initially clear whether women were eligible to serve on the council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Two were elected; however, Margaret Mansfield, Baroness Sandhurst's election was overturned on petition from a losing candidate, Beresford Hope.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] Jane Cobden avoided participating in council business for the first year, in the hope that this would prevent her election from being challenged.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] In 1890, she began participating, and was then taken to court by Walter De Souza, and fined for acting while disqualified.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] She remained a council member, alongside the alderman Emma Cons, and attended meetings, but neither took any further part in votes.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] On 5 February, 19 aldermen were elected, to also join the council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1889-london-county-council-election] 18 of them were supported by the Progressive Party, and only 4 by the Moderates (three being on both party lists).
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The Progressives argued that a political party system was necessary on the council, and that the Conservative Party had attempted to discredit the party's leadership of the council, for the benefit of the opposition Moderates.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The party called for the council to be given powers over the Metropolitan Police, and the city's water supply and tramways.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The Moderates did not conduct a centralised campaign, but the Conservative Party worked in support of the group.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] It argued that a formal party system would lead to corruption, and that the Progressives were at fault for developing one.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] It also campaigned against Irish home rule.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] Thompson, one of the Progressive candidates in Strand was disqualified as he did not live in the division.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] Working as a barrister, he had supplied the address of his chambers on the nomination papers, but this was not deemed suitable qualification.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] Although the previous election was not conducted on formal party lines, the elected members had either joined the Progressives or aligned with the Moderate group, so it was possible to track the changes to the council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The Progressives won 11 more seats than in 1889, at the expense of the Moderates.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The Moderate gained a single seat, in Holborn.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1892-london-county-council-election] The *Manchester Guardian* argued that the Progressives would be unable to carry out much of their programme, as it fell outside the council's remit; but that if the Liberal Party won the upcoming 1892 UK general election, it might be given responsibilities in these additional areas.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1895-london-county-council-election] The Progressives campaigned on their record of running the council, arguing that they had achieved far more than the Metropolitan Board of Works had, and also that the various Metropolitan Borough Councils should be unified and their powers given to the London County Council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1895-london-county-council-election] The Moderates argued that the Progressives had delayed in making improvements, and that measures should be taken to increase home ownership rates, rather than constructing council housing.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1895-london-county-council-election] The Earl of Onslow, a prominent figure in the Conservative Party, was expected to stand for the Moderates in Islington South, but he was disqualified as his nomination papers were not received in time.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1895-london-county-council-election] The Moderates gained 23 seats from the Progressives, and lost only one seat to them, tying both parties on 59 seats.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1895-london-county-council-election] Although the result was a tie, the Progressives held the majority of aldermanic seats on the council, and thus were able to retain control of it.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] The Progressives contended that, because the last election had resulted in a tie in the number of councillors, the council had made little progress over the past three years.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] They argued that they had successfully led slum clearance programmes.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] They proposed that the council should maintain its existing policy of refusing to sell alcohol in premises it owned, should seek to levy increased taxes on landlords, and should aim to municipalise the gas and water supplies.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] The Moderates argued that the Progressives were fighting on party political lines, and that as a result, they would too.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] They contended that the Progressives wanted to adopt socialist policies, and that they had wasted money by overspending on building projects.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] Instead, the Moderates advocated passing the majority of the council's responsibilities to the Metropolitan Borough Councils.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] The election in Hackney Central was delayed, due to the death of one of the candidates.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] The Progressive Party gained 16 seats from the Moderates and lost only 4 seats to them, winning a substantial majority.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1898-london-county-council-election] *The Times* noted that this was less than their majority in the 1892 London County Council election, and did not necessarily mean that the voters of London would support the Liberal Party at the next UK general election.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] Since the 1901 London County Council election, the electorate for the council had increased by 19,221, the increase being in the outlying boroughs, while most inner city boroughs lost voters.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] Turnout was also reported as being higher in the outer boroughs.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] All the seats were contested other than Deptford and Greenwich, which were held uncontested by the Progressive Party.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] The main issue at the election was education policy, as the London School Board was to be abolished and its powers absorbed by the council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] *The Times* argued that the Conservative Party candidates had undoubted loyalty to the Church of England, whereas the Progressive Party candidates might have sympathy towards dissenters.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] Other issues were the attitude of candidates towards the employment of Chinese immigrants in South Africa, and the purchase of the county council of some rails manufactured in Belgium.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] The Progressive Party lost one seat, while the Municipal Reform Party gained four, and independents fell from four seats to one.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1904-london-county-council-election] Nine members of the School Board won seats on the new council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1906-london-local-elections] All council seats in all 28 metropolitan boroughs were up for election.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1906-london-local-elections] The results were a landslide victory for the Conservatives, who stood as Municipal Reformers.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1906-london-local-elections] The Municipal Reformers won 22 boroughs.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1906-london-local-elections] This compared to three for the Liberals, who stood as Progressives, two for Independents and the nascent Labour Party losing its only borough, Woolwich.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The **1998 Greater London Authority referendum** was held in Greater London on 7 May 1998.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The referendum asked whether there was support for creating a Greater London Authority composed of a directly elected Mayor of London and a London Assembly to scrutinise the Mayor's actions.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The referendum was held under the Greater London Authority (Referendum) Act 1998 provisions.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Polling day coincided with the 1998 London local elections.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Labour's 1997 general election manifesto, *New Labour, New Life for Britain,* mentioned establishing a directly elected mayor and authority.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] This would be the first London-wide government since the abolition of the Greater London Council.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The government published a green paper with the title *New Leadership for London* in July 1997.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] This laid out the principles of the GLA: a strong mayor and a "strategic" assembly.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The full proposals were confirmed in a March 1998 white paper entitled *A* *Mayor and Assembly for London* which set out the full details of the proposal.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] Voters were permitted to select either a simple **YES** or **NO** answer.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The 'Yes' vote won in every London Borough, though support was generally larger in Inner London than in Outer London.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The lowest support figures were 60.5% in Havering and 57.1% in Bromley; the greatest were 83.8% in Haringey and 81.8% in Lambeth.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The income level of boroughs was an even greater factor affecting the outcome.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The government passed the Greater London Authority Act 1999, creating the Greater London Authority.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The first elections for the Mayor of London and the London Assembly were held in May 2000.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The Conservatives criticised the referendum's low turnout, and suggested that it undermined the legitimacy of the referendum.
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The Labour Party refuted this suggestion, by instead suggesting that many people had decided to not vote because they perceived the result as a foregone conclusion, and that there was significant enthusiasm for a "strong, independent, political voice that can speak up for Londoners".
[src:1998-greater-london-authority-referendum/1998-greater-london-authority-referendum] The establishment of directly elected mayors was suggested as possibly as constitutionally significant as Scottish devolution or Welsh devolution.
